<HEADLINE>
FT  05 DEC 94 / Company News (This Week): Raised glasses should show a fair
head - S&amp;N/Bass
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Two brewers' results this week will exemplify the industry's trends and
investors' intentions. Scottish &amp; Newcastle, reporting today, has
outperformed Bass, reporting on Wednesday, in both beer and stock markets.
They share beer and leisure as their two main lines of business, but
Scottish &amp; Newcastle has done better than Bass in both. The main factors
behind a rise in its interim pre-tax profits to about Pounds 145m from
Pounds 109m are the acquisition of the Chef &amp; Brewer pub chain and expansion
of its Center Parcs holiday villages. Brewing profits could be slightly
ahead thanks to cost savings.
Scottish &amp; Newcastle is not the darling of the sector, however. The
speculation that it might pick up some or all of Courage is making investors
cautious.
Bass is expected to report a more modest rise in pre-tax profits for the
year ended September to about Pounds 540m from Pounds 508m. Its brewing
margins are likely to have slipped because of discounting and
rationalisation costs while it has done well to hold volume in a market down
about 1 per cent. Its pub estate has enjoyed a pick-up in profits, but it is
less well-developed than some others in, for example, food.
On the positive side, Holiday Inns has enjoyed rising occupancy and room
rates, particularly in the US. Under firmer management, it is raising the
standards of laggard hotels in its chain while expanding rapidly worldwide.
The good news for investors is that Bass appears to be changing its tune
slightly on beer. In the past its ambition was to defend its leading market
share, currently 23 per cent. Heavy discounting, particularly against
Courage, took a toll on profits. It still wants to be number one but it
placed more emphasis on profits and brand development in its trading update
two months ago.
</TEXT>
