<HEADLINE>
FT  05 DEC 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There was a golden age of childhood in the late Victorian and Edwardian
periods, to judge from the great children's books of the time: E. Nesbit,
Kenneth Grahame, JM Barrie, the greatest of them marked by an underlying
sadness - perhaps at innocence lost or consciousness of how different the
adult world be from the youthful ideal.
At least it made a change from the days when children were considered little
adults. The history of how we look at childhood, how sacrosanct, fleeting
and vulnerable adults may have considered it, is the subject of The End of
Childhood (11.15pm BBC2).
The heavy-breathing Sarah Dunant, looking more than ever like the travesti
caricature of a Late Show presenter, touches on such fascinating questions
as whether present-day kids are actually young any more, what the nature of
innocence is, or whether it ever existed. I suspect we have turned full
circle and kids are little adults again; but this time on equal terms with
the big ones.
</TEXT>
