<HEADLINE>
FT  05 DEC 94 / This Week: Film/Video
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL ANDREWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Just when you thought it was safe to pack the children off to the cinema to
be engulfed by Disney revivals, here comes a wave of semi-radical sci-fi.
After Frankenstein everyone in the movies is tinkering with life, birth and
death.
We kick off with the comedy variant. In Junior, scientist Arnold
Schwarzenegger is made pregnant by fellow boffin Danny De Vito. Not, we
hurriedly add, in anything like the traditional way. De Vito invents a drug
which as side-effect can make men conceive. Whom better to try it on than
his colleague, played by a man whose whole life has been spent making his
body swell in strange places? Ivan Twins Reitman directs; Schwarzenegger
gamely dons the stomach padding; and rave reviews precede the film from
across the Atlantic.
Children may be unscathed by Junior, but think twice before risking them on
Cronos. This Mexican horror film is the grand guignol hit of the 1994 film
festival season.
A macabre gold bauble with mobile claws impales victims' flesh, thereby
conferring immortality. Several strange characters chase it and each other
around Mexico City, as the film turns into the year's wittiest, most sleekly
shot essay in modern Gothic. Writer-director Guillermo Del Toro is already
in Hollywood fielding movie offers.
Add The Shadow, The Nightmare Before Christmas and the new gay ghost story
To Die For - a British black comedy remaking Ghost with a
boy-meets-boy/boy-loses-boy/boy-is-haunted-by-boy slant - and we wonder if
we aren't in the afterglow of Halloween rather than the run-up to Christmas.
You can always take a break from heavy-duty big screen fantasy. Leave your
stocking out at night to be filled with videos and Santa Claus may deposit
Naked In New York. A cast of ancient and modern luminaries - Kathleen
Turner, Tony Curtis, Jill Clayburgh, Quentin Crisp - swap high-class banter
in a tangy comedy of Manhattan manners.
Or Santa may leave you The Last Seduction; the sly, dark tale of a woman
crook (Linda Fiorentino) dabbling in sex, murder and film noir stylistics.
As we said, the times may not be very Christmassy. But who says we adults
don't need a festive break too from time to time?
</TEXT>
