<HEADLINE>
FT  05 DEC 94 / This Week: 'Golf's next god' - Sport
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEITH WHEATLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Golfing statistics tell us that the vast majority of enthusiastic amateurs
never shoot better than 90 in their playing careers. So eat your hearts out
as I tell you of a boy who scored 84 in his first-ever round of golf.
'I was seven years old and shorter than every club except the putter,'
recalls Ernie Els, now a formidably broad 25-year-old and 6ft 3ins tall.
This year has been Els' annus mirablis. His victory in the US Open came
after an opening European Tour win at the Desert Classic in Dubai. It was
nailed down in October by a scintillating performance to secure the World
Matchplay championship at Wentworth. No one inside golf doubts that Els will
be taking the silverware home for many years to come.
The predictions are shivery in their intensity and unanimity. 'I think I
just played with the next god,' commented Curtis Strange (renowned as a
sourpuss) after partnering Els in the US Open. 'The last young guy I saw who
could touch Ernie was Seve Ballesteros 15 years ago,' says Open champion
Nick Price. 'He's young enough, strong enough and long enough to win any
tournament he tees up in,' was Greg Norman's verdict, after Els shot 61 and
took three shots off the course record on the opening day at Dubai.
Now Ernie is back home in his native South Africa. This weekend he played
before huge galleries of adoring fans at the Million Dollar Challenge in Sun
City. It is quite something for an amiable but somewhat reserved young man
to become a virtual national monument in a sports-mad country that can't
quite forgive Gary Player for growing old.
Early last week I caught up with Els, doing his sponsor a favour by
participating in a low-key pro-am event on the aptly named Wild Coast, 120
miles south of Durban. His two amateur partners, marketing executives from a
photocopier company, were near helpless with nerves, after being drawn to
play with the icon.
The gallery around the tee was decidely intimidating as Mike Brown duffed
his first shot and saw it trickle 20 yards down the fairway. Els smiled and
whispered something that had the blushing salesman actually laughing as he
marched towards the green.
There is no doubt that South Africans are on the verge of a great love
affair. On the eve of the US Open's final day a good luck fax message
hand-written by vice-president FW de Klerk was delivered to Els' hotel room.
From the recipient's perspective, such a wall of adoration and expectation
can begin to look less than attractive. 'On the tour it's been no problem.
It is when you get home that the hassle starts,' he reflected over a few
Castle lagers and a spin of the roulette wheel at the Wild Coast casino.
'Suddenly everyone wants to shake my hand and ask why I didn't play well
last week in Japan. Sorry mate, it's been a long year,' said Els, in
bitter-sweet mood. 'I don't like going into a bar or restaurant and being
recognised. People just come up to you when you're in the middle of eating.
The best place for me to go out right now is London. Nobody there gives a
damn who you are,' he added.
Irritation and exasperation at this new development in his life are
detectable just below the sunny exterior. Ernie's face is his misfortune. A
permanent grin beneath a thatch of blonde hair makes him as approachable as
Nick Faldo is forbidding. Chatting to Els in the public area of a hotel is
like trying to talk to your boss while running the till at Sainsbury's.
Every few minutes a new well-wisher stops by. Many are fellow players,
journeyman pros from the Sunshine Tour, friends from the old days - only
1993, in fact, but it might as well be in the history books in terms of
where Els is going.
'If Ernie stayed here, he'd probably win every event, every year,' says a
peer. It's obvious why he won't. And the demands of 15 events on the US tour
next year, half-a-dozen exemptions for European tournaments, plus a few
big-buck events in Japan, mean that the fans back home are most likely to
watch Els on television.
It won't be popular in a country with a natural tendency to see the rest of
the world from a laager. Els himself is smart enough to nurse a slight
foreboding. 'They put you up on this pedestal and its so easy for them to
pull you down again if you don't do exactly what they want. The knife starts
going in,' he reflected. 'It happened to Naas Botha here and to Greg Norman
in Australia.'
He makes the point that in 1993, when he won an extraordinary six
consecutive tournaments in South Africa, there was very little fuss made of
him. A year later he enjoys a few big wins overseas and the cry goes up
'Where's Ernie?'
It would be easier to bear if he were a natural, rootless cosmopolitan,
slipping effortlessly from Europe, to the US, to Japan. But he's not. Ernie
comes from an intensely family-orientated background in the affluent
Johannesburg suburb of Germiston. There's a putting green in the
back-garden, laid and tended a decade ago by father Neels, for young Ernie
to practise on. Another casualty. Fed up with intense celebrity of life in
the Golden City, Els is building a seaside home for himself and fiancee
Liesl in the small town of George, two hours' drive from Cape Town, but a
thousand miles from home. The Germiston putting green won't be getting much
use. Mr Els snr. has put his plans to re-plant the grass on hold.
</TEXT>
