FT  05 DEC 94 / This Week: Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALKARIM JIVANI, TV Editor, Time Out
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Without Walls (Tuesday 9.00-9.30pm) does a piece on The Battersea Bardot,
aka Carol White, who hit the big-time - not to mention the bottle in the
1960s. After her appearances in Cathy Come Home and Poor Cow, there was
strong demand for her services from directors as diverse as Ken Loach and
Michael Winner. A poignant profile of a woman who was going to be a star,
but ended up as a black hole.
Now that politics is more about kissing babies than killing rivals, does
Machiavelli have any relevance? Timewatch (Sunday 9.00-9.50pm, BBC2) asks
David Mellor, Roy Hattersley, John Biffen, Clare Short and Sir Bernard
Ingham whether 'The Prince' can still provide any useful pointers. The
answer, surprisingly, is yes if Mrs Thatcher is used as a test case.
The slogan 'retail is detail' is drummed into every Marks and Spencer
employee, as High Interest (Sunday 5.10-6.00pm, C4) reveals, with board
members worrying about the amount of potato in the Vichysoisse. The
behind-the-scenes glimpses of M&amp;S at work are fascinating.
