<HEADLINE>
FT  05 DEC 94 / This Week: FT Guide to World Trade Organisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Why is the WTO being created?
To strengthen management of the world trade system and global economic
integration. The WTO will have a more formal structure, bigger powers and a
wider remit than the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, which has
operated on a 'provisional' basis since its inception in 1947. WTO members
must also accept all the organisation's provisions, whereas Gatt allows
countries not to subscribe to some of its agreements.
How many countries will belong to the WTO?
All Gatt's 124 members, once they have ratified the Uruguay Round world
trade agreement. More than 20 other countries want to join, including China,
Russia, Taiwan, Ukraine and Vietnam.
Who will head the WTO?
Gatt members are supposed to choose this week between three candidates:
former Mexican president Carlos Salinas, former Italian trade minister
Renato Ruggiero and South Korean trade minister Kim Chul-su. However,
political wrangling may delay a decision until next year. In that event,
Peter Sutherland, Gatt's outgoing director-general, might stay on as a
temporary caretaker.
How much will it cost to run?
A SFr105m budget is proposed for next year, a small rise on the current
budget of the Gatt secretariat, whose roughly 400 employees will staff the
WTO. Gatt is lean compared with other international bodies, and most
governments want the WTO to stay that way. That is one reason why they
decided recently to keep it out of the clutches of the United Nations.
What will the WTO do?
Its immediate priorities will be to implement the Uruguay Round agreements
and complete outstanding negotiations on issues such as liberalising trade
in services. Its longer-term agenda may include the treatment of foreign
investment and links between trade and environment, competition policy and
possibly labour standards. These are all complex and politically
controversial subjects, which impinge directly on countries' domestic
policies.
How will it take decisions?
Like Gatt, the WTO plans to operate by consensus. However, this may become
harder as the centre of global economic gravity continues to shift from the
US and Europe, which have traditionally held sway in Gatt, towards
developing countries, notably in Asia. China's entry, in particular, is
expected to have a far-reaching impact on the WTO.
What new powers will the WTO have to enforce international rules?
It will have stronger and speedier mechanisms for settling international
trade disputes. An important innovation is that WTO dispute panels' rulings
will apply unless there is a consensus to reject them - the reverse of Gatt
practice.
So US critics are right to say that control over national trade policies is
being handed to faceless bureaucrats?
No more so than under Gatt. The WTO cannot compel members to accept rulings
they disagree with, though it can authorise other countries to retaliate in
such cases. Disputes panels' authority will depend heavily on establishing
confidence in their fairness, integrity and judicial rigour. In any case,
WTO members are free to withdraw from the body at six months' notice.
Will WTO members still be able to resort to unilateral trade measures?
The US and the EU say they reserve the right unilaterally to press for
concessions from countries which are not WTO members, or in areas where
there are no clear WTO rules.
Will there ever be any more big world trade rounds?
No one is sure. Exhausted by the eight-year Uruguay Round marathon, many
Gatt members hope the WTO will end such ordeals by developing into a
permanent negotiating forum. But some think it may be hard to make big
breakthroughs without the political momentum and scope for trade-offs which
omnibus rounds generate.
What will happen to Gatt?
It will continue temporarily, but governments are expected to agree soon on
a deadline for winding it up after the WTO gets into its stride.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XAZ  World.
</CN>
<XX>
