<HEADLINE>
FT  05 DEC 94 / Architecture: Model for the millennium - Colin Amery on the
high standards set by Westminster Cathedral
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By COLIN AMERY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Architecture and anniversaries seem to be inextricably linked, especially as
we approach the millennium. The announcement last week that the Millennium
Commission (which seems to be anxious to model itself on the Victorian
Commissioners of the Great Exhibition of 1851) is planning to support 12
major capital projects around the UK with 50 per cent of its Lottery income,
represents a major boost for architecture.
In the recent past there would have been no hesitation about what kind of
building you would erect to commemorate almost anything - you would build a
church or a cathedral. Today the lack of certainty about any system of
spiritual, rather than material, values makes commemorative buildings
difficult to conceive. There have been too many great exhibitions that are
usually meaningless in themselves, and they always result in empty 'expo'
sites, littering the world with their fantasies. One only has to think of
the Atomium in Brussels: the decaying geodesic domes from the New York World
Fair on the road into that city from Kennedy Airport; the crumbling Habitat
structures in Montreal and the collapsing remnants of Expo '92 - now looking
for a use in Seville.
How wise of the Hungarian Government to decide that it does not want to
waste money on any great expo in Budapest, and that it would rather build
more usefully and gradually for the future of the country.
Although the Millennium Commissioners have asked for all submissions for
these great capital projects to be of 'high architectural design and
environmental quality', there is absolutely no guarantee or system of
accountability that can reliably ensure that this is going to be the case.
The curious English system of entrusting almost everything to a well meaning
group of amateurs to judge the professionals has its virtues, but it also
has its limitations. There are some lessons from the past that can be
helpful when it comes to commissioning buildings and there is a particular
centenary coming next year that is significant. The great Roman Catholic
cathedral of Westminster will celebrate its first hundred years next year,
and mark this event by an important architectural exhibition.
It is significant that the catholic hierarchy in the 1890s attempted an
architectural competition that was a complete failure. In the end they
decided to choose the architect simply on the basis of the quality of his
work. The choice of John Francis Bentley was inspired and appropriate. He
understood both the aesthetic and functional ideas of the brief, and indeed
the political significance of the building of a new catholic cathedral
almost within the purlieus of Westminster Abbey.
I think that Westminster Cathedral (left) is one of the great buildings of
England. It is undoubtedly the greatest work of Bentley - and yet it is
still a somewhat under appreciated masterpiece. It has, for me, all the
qualities of a major piece of architecture.
These qualities are due to the very simplicity of the idea behind the
cathedral - it had to be cheaply built, as it was entirely funded by the
contributions of the faithful, and it had one very clear purpose - not the
triumphalism of the Church but the visibility of the celebration of the
Mass.
The cathedral is living proof of the continuation of the highest standards
of craftsmanship in England. Many of the marble floors, for example, were
only completed in the 1950s. The adoption of the Byzantine style for the
cathedral was extraordinary at the end of the 19th century and there are
those who would still consider it bizarre for London at the end of the 20th
century. But it is such a miraculous building in the atmosphere it creates
and the sense it gives of being, not in any sense a stylistic revival, but a
place with an integrity that is entirely its own.
There are not, as far as I can see, any plans for any new cathedrals to mark
 -what is, after all, the Millennium of Christ. Indeed, in the Millennium
Commissioners' report there is no mention of the Christian significance of
the event at all. Perhaps they should give all the money raised from the
lottery to the cathedrals of England - their need is great and there is no
need at all for the nonsense that the commissioners are currently cooking up
after their long tour of this island and their endless chats with the
worthy. I can think of no more worthy cause than the restoration and
endowment of the cathedrals of England for ever as a mark of the Christian
Millennium. I notice that the atheistic report on the cathedrals that Lady
Howe has just published is far more interested in the legal and 'management'
aspects of the cathedrals than in their role as spiritual storehouses and
beacons of enlightenment.
It is my opinion that her report should be ignored and the example of the
active, powerful and 'still under construction' 100-year-old cathedral of
Westminster should be the model for this millennium and beyond.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
