<HEADLINE>
FT  05 DEC 94 / Call for change to accounts degrees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY, Accountancy Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A research report published today by the Association of Certified
Accountants calls for an urgent review of undergraduate accounting courses.
The authors claim that courses 'have merely pandered to students'
expectations of an accounting degree as a preliminary - and thus perceived
necessary - stage of professional accountancy training'.
The report says that it is wrong to allow the curriculum to be dominated by
what it calls 'technicist' views which prepare the students to enter
professional training in one of the Big Six accountancy firms.
'The fact is that opportunities for graduates to enter into professional
accountancy training through the Big Six are rapidly shrinking with those
from the 'new' universities being particularly affected,' say the authors.
They put forward an alternative approach based on accounting studies rooted
in social science - accounting which would look beyond profit and loss to
aspects such as environmental and social impact.
The authors, accountancy academics, also argue that those students equipped
with such a broader accounting education would be better suited to enter the
Big Six. 'Current accounting degrees, the core content of which appears to
be largely watered down versions of the professional syllabus, do not
achieve this,' they say.
Social and Environmental Accounting Education in British Universities by
David Owen, Christopher Humphrey and Linda Lewis. ACCA, PO Box 66, Glasgow,
G41 IBS. Pounds 9.95.
</TEXT>
