<HEADLINE>
FT  05 DEC 94 / Ministers act to defuse row on executive pay increases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Senior ministers are considering ways of promoting tighter shareholder
control over executive salary increases after a Commons row about a 75 per
cent pay rise for the chief executive of British Gas.
Mr David Hunt, the cabinet's chief political troubleshooter, started looking
at ways of defusing the issue after Mr John Major, the prime minister,
condemned 'unjustified' pay increases last month during question time
exchanges with Mr Tony Blair, the Labour leader.
Mr Hunt met senior ministers including Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor,
and Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, to explore ways of
reducing the potential for damage to the government.
Cabinet colleagues say that Mr Major and Mr Clarke were 'livid' about Mr
Cedric Brown's pay rise, which followed public concern about substantial
salary increases in the privatised water companies. Some ministers believe
that the row has seriously undermined the case for privatisation by fuelling
Labour claims that it amounts to little more than a chance for public-sector
managers to make a financial killing.
However, Mr Hunt's soundings failed to identify an easy solution to the
salaries problem, which has been referred to the cabinet's standing
committee on industrial and consumer affairs. Ideas include amending company
law to require salary increases to be approved by a weighted majority of
shareholders and giving regulators of privatised industries powers to
investigate salaries as well as prices.
Neither proposal has attracted much support from ministers, who are wary of
appearing to interfere in the salary arrangements of private-sector
companies.
The most likely outcome is a greater effort by ministers to persuade
shareholders to use their existing powers under the companies acts to
control executive pay through resolutions at annual meetings. These powers
are rarely used because few small investors take an active part in company
affairs.
Mr Major used a Commons written answer last week to point out that
institutional investment funds, which control most large public companies,
can influence events 'behind the scenes'.
But senior ministers are privately dismissive of the scope for meaningful
action by managers of institutional funds, who are said to be uninterested
in controlling the salaries of their executive colleagues.
Ministers have also reopened an inquiry launched a year ago by Mr Stephen
Dorrell, the then Treasury financial secretary, into the level of dividends.
The review was shelved after the publication of a letter to Mr Dorrell from
Lord Hanson accusing the minister of 'sounding like a socialist'.
</TEXT>
