FT  05 DEC 94 / Funds to consider role over salaries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A group of leading institutional investors will meet later this week to
consider how to respond to calls from government ministers for shareholders
to have a greater say in deciding executive pay packages.
The investment committee of the National Association of Pension Funds will
meet on Friday to discuss executive pay, Mr Geoff Lindey, the committee
chairman said. 'We will be considering whether we should be more involved
(in deciding executive pay levels) and if so, how,' he added.
Two weeks ago Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, said in the Commons that
shareholders might be given increased powers to curb excessive pay increases
for top company executives.
Mr Clarke revealed that the practical issues involved were under examination
as the government came under renewed pressure to condemn the rise awarded to
the chief executive of British Gas.
Some shareholder groups had urged the Cadbury Committee, when it was
considering a code of conduct for corporate boards of directors, to allow
shareholders final approval over terms of directors' contracts.
However, the association did not back that view, saying it would be
impossible to persuade senior executives to take key posts if the terms of
their contracts could later be vetoed by shareholder groups.
Other issues likely to be discussed by the association will be the role of
pension benefits in total remuneration.
