<HEADLINE>
FT  05 DEC 94 / Machine tool chiefs to meet Treasury
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Leaders of the Machine Tool Technologies Association are to meet officials
from the Treasury on Wednesday to hear why manufacturing industry's plea for
increased capital allowances was rejected in last week's Budget.
Mr Stan Vaughan, association president, will head the delegation which is
likely to express disappointment at the short shrift given by Mr Kenneth
Clarke, the chancellor, to the pleas.
The association, which represents Britain's machine tool builders, was one
of seven industrial associations which wrote to Mr Clarke in October asking
for increased allowances to stimulate 'permanently higher levels' of
industrial investment.
But Mr Clarke said in his Budget speech that the argument for higher
allowances had a 'simplistic appeal' and would distort investment decisions.
He restated the government's philosophy of favouring lower overall
corporation tax rather than higher allowances.
Ironically, forecasts released by the association late last week predict
strong growth over the next three years in machine-tool investment in the UK
and substantial increases in exports of machine tools.
According to forecasts for the association by Mr John Walker of Oxford
Economic Forecasting, sales of machine tools in the UK market will grow from
Pounds 280m next year to Pounds 345m in 1996 and Pounds 380m in 1997.
This reflects the significant improvement in company finances and relatively
low interest rates. Also, says the association, the need to invest to
maintain competitiveness will become increasingly important.
The buoyant forecast for investment could be used as an argument against
increased capital allowances, as it suggests that such a stimulus is not
needed because of the upturn in industry's fortunes. But the association and
other associations such as the Engineering Employers Federation have argued
that under-investment is a long-term problem.
The forecasts are derived from market surveys by the association and are
based on a narrower definition of machine tools than that used for regular
Central Statistical Office figures on the industry.
</TEXT>
