FT  05 DEC 94 / Revenue examines tax on charities
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Inland Revenue yesterday promised to re-examine a tax change announced
in the Budget that may have the side-effect of imposing big tax bills on
many charities.
Tax officials conceded they had not intended to hit charities when drawing
up plans to close a loophole used by foreign companies with subsidiaries in
the UK. They promised to listen to charities' concerns and did not rule out
re-wording clauses planned for next year's finance bill.
The Revenue is worried that some UK subsidiaries are able to avoid
corporation tax by using profits to make interest payments. These have not
previously been taxable. The plan to tax such payments would affect UK
companies only where the company receiving the interest was not paying
corporation tax. But that could include many large charities with trading
subsidiaries.
Letters, Page 14
