<HEADLINE>
FT  05 DEC 94 / Industry supports pro-EU Tories
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Some of Britain's leading industrial companies - including Glaxo, Grand
Metropolitan and Enterprise Oil - have given financial backing to a new
pro-European pressure group inside the Conservative party.
As Tory Euro-rebels continue to challenge Mr John Major's government over
European Union integration, the new group, called Action Centre for Europe,
is to lead a fight-back by Conservatives committed to British membership of
the EU.
The group was founded by Lord Howe, the former cabinet minister, earlier
this year. Among senior politicians who have joined its advisory council are
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, Mr David Hunt, the chancellor of the
Duchy of Lancaster, and Sir Leon Brittan, one of the UK's EU commissioners.
A group of banks and business organisations have already pledged about
Pounds 50,000 to set up the organisation, which will argue the pro-European
case within the Tory party in the run up to the EU's inter-governmental
conference in 1996.
The list of sponsors includes Salomon Brothers, the merchant bank. It is
understood that strong interest in the organisation has also been shown by
NM Rothschild, the merchant bank, De La Rue, the bank note printer, Pirelli,
the Italian tyremaker, and the Andersen Consulting group. ICL and General
Utilities have also shown interest.
Representatives of some of these organisations attended a lunch in London
last Friday hosted by Sir Leon Brittan and Lord Tugendhat, chairman of Abbey
National bank.
According to Conservative party sources, the centre will provide information
to MPs and public figures about European issues. It is to launch a series of
high-profile conferences next year outlining how the UK can develop in the
EU.
It aims to counter the role of the European Foundation, an anti-Maastricht
think-tank.
'The anti-Europeans get lots of information and help from the European
Foundation,' said one of the centre's leading figures. 'I would hope that
pro-Europeans would get the same from us.'
The development of the group is being seen by senior Conservatives as
another indication that the pro-European wing of the party is preparing to
wage a tough fight for its principles.
Last week it was reported that the party as a whole had suffered a big fall
in cash gifts from companies. The Labour Research Department, an
organisation funded mainly by unions, said its researchers could find only
168 companies that had made donations in the year to March to the
Conservative party - the lowest such figure its annual survey had ever
found.
</TEXT>
