<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / A-Z of Personal Finance (25): Make money abroad from home
territory - Xenophobia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARBARA ELLIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Xenophobia, literally fear or hatred of foreigners, has been making an
unfortunate comeback in unscrupulous political circles around the world, but
continues to look extremely out of place in investment, where global
thinking is considered essential.
But in its wider definition - fear of strange customs - xenophobia could be
taken to mean no more than an aversion to the unfamiliar settlement systems
or currency dealing involved in buying and selling overseas investments.
Creatively treated, this phobia can be used to seek out British-based
companies with a high proportion of sales or earnings abroad. Investors can
then have the convenience of buying foreign earnings from home territory in
sterling, and may be able to secure tax advantages not normally available on
investments in some geographical areas.
For example, investors who want to hold investment trust shares in a
personal eguity plan, out of reach of capital gains and income taxes, have
to ensure that at least 50 per cent of the trust's portfolio is in countries
belonging to the European Union. But there is no similar geographical limit
for investors buying shares in individual industrial or financial companies
to place under a Pep shelter. So although Bunzl derives 63 per cent of its
sales from the US, Fisons 62 per cent and Grand Metropolitan 60 per cent,
all are fully eligible for Peps.
Analysts at BZW track UK companies' geographical sales exposure on a monthly
basis, using historic figures from annual reports and the firm's own
earnings forecasts for the next two years.
Analyst Steve Wright explained that BZW also took into account companies
exposed to the US dollar without necessarily selling anything in the US,
such as BP, Shell and British Airways, all buyers of oil; or
commodity-related stocks such as RTZ.
BZW mid-November figures reveal RTZ as an ideal stock for xenophobes with
investment wanderlust, offering just 1 per cent exposure to the UK market,
against 28 per cent in the Asia-Pacific region.
Zeneca is the next least reliant on Britain, with just 7 per cent exposure
to the UK against 45 per cent to the US and 15 per cent to Asia and the
Pacific. By comparison, Glaxo's UK/US exposure is 9 per cent/45 per cent.
Hanson's much advertised 'over there/over here' turns out to mean 45 per
cent of sales in the US and 43 per cent in Britain.
And there are no Eurosceptics in the building materials sector, judging by
the European exposure of RMC Group (67 per cent), BPB Industries (56 per
cent) and Redland (52 per cent).
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    XAZ  World.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6289 Security and Commodity Services, NEC.
    P6211 Security Brokers and Dealers.
    P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
