<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / The Lex Column: Attwoods
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Attwoods' white knight entered from stage right, strutted on the scene for
less than five hours and promptly exited stage left. Yesterday's
intervention by Ikotek, an unknown subsidiary of an obscure Canadian
company, proved irrelevant: shareholders controlling substantially less than
1 per cent of Attwoods' equity withdrew from initial acceptance of
Browning-Ferris Industries' offer.
Once BFI had raised its offer last month, Attwoods was left defending the
indefensible. From the start, Attwoods' management admitted the powerful
industrial logic behind combining the two businesses. Its only strategy was
to complain about the price. Attwoods insisted shareholders would receive
more if the company were broken up. However, it gave no figure for the
break-up value or names of companies interested in buying a piece. Worse,
there was no guarantee that the scheme would actually be implemented. Given
the choice between a promised break-up in six months and cash today, the
decision by the majority of shareholders to accept BFI's finely priced offer
was not a surprise.
The task before Attwoods' advisers was not easy and they may console
themselves that at least BFI was forced to raise its offer. However, the
combination of SG Warburg and Robert Fleming is clearly an unlucky one. It
is the same that advised Enterprise on its disastrous bid for Lasmo.
</TEXT>
