<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / Bosnia group's peace efforts falter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK, LAURA SILBER and MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, BELGRADE, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Foreign ministers from the US, its European allies and Russia called last
night for a ceasefire throughout Bosnia but failed to come up with any new
ideas for promoting peace.
The failure came in the wake of another ill-tempered row between Nato and
the UN over Bosnia with the UN unsuccessfully pressing the alliance to scale
down its air activity.
After a longer-than-expected meeting the so-called contact group on Bosnia -
comprising the US, Russia, Britain, France and Germany - reaffirmed their
existing peace plan which would divide Bosnia 51-49 between a Croat-Moslem
federation and a Serb zone.
They also confirmed the idea that Bosnia must at least continue to exist as
a state within its current borders.
However, ministers failed to bridge the group's internal differences on some
central questions, and failed to spell out any new threats or incentives to
the warring parties.
Mr Andre Kozyrev, Russian foreign minister, said: 'Of course not as much was
achieved as would have been desirable.' But he welcomed the fact that the US
had joined its partners in ruling out military solutions and supporting the
continued presence of UN forces in Bosnia.
The five ministers failed to bridge their differences on how Serbian
president Slobodan Milosevic should be rewarded if he makes further
concessions to the peace process.
The lack of new ideas came as Nato pledged to continue military flights over
Bosnia, in spite of a request from the UN to scale them down, in the latest
in a series of rows between the two international organisations.
The Nato flights, designed to police the skies over Bosnia, highlight the
military alliance's intention to remain active in the region. However, UN
officials have accused Nato of 'cowboy tactics' in the air which have
complicated negotiations with the Bosnian Serbs.
In a bid to salvage the UN mission in Bosnia and secure the release of some
500 detained peacekeepers, Mr Yasushi Akashi, the UN special envoy, met
Bosnian Serb leaders in Pale, their stronghold above Sarajevo. He said last
night they had agreed to release the peacekeepers detained after Nato air
strikes two weeks ago.
Mr Warren Christopher, the US secretary of state, was concerned earlier
yesterday about the impact of upgraded Serb anti-aircraft missiles on the
policing flights. He said there could be some 'operational changes'.
</TEXT>
