<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / FT Christmas Books: The pick of the publishing year - From
politics to poetry, history to humour - our writers choose the best books of
1994
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL THOMPSON-NOEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The novel is not dead, nor even in trouble, despite what the rubbish-heads
say. A highlight of my fictional year was Melanie Rae Thon's Iona Moon
(Penguin, Pounds 5.99), about a farmer's girl in White Falls, Idaho, who
smells of the byre and is generous with her favours, coming to terms with
small-town life and its unforgiving righteousness. Thon's talent is
reminiscent of Peter Carey's: distinctive, sharply lyrical and based on
masterly characterisation.
Also very good: Masai Dreaming, by Justin Cartwright (Picador, Pounds 5.99),
a stunningly well-realised tale of a would-be movie scriptwriter researching
the story of a young Frenchwoman, Claudia, who lived among the Masai before
being sent from Paris, days before its liberation, to Auschwitz. Complex,
sad, poetic. 'Whatever happens to me,' writes Claudia to the Masai in her
last, unbearable message, 'I wish that you may have many cattle and
plentiful green grass. And wherever God takes me I will dream of you.'
Honourable near-miss, but memorable and enjoyable: Thomas Keneally's
too-ambitious Jacko The Great Intruder (Hodder &amp; Stoughton, Pounds 15.99), a
tale of TV folk (monsters, all). This is Keneally's 22nd novel, and has
enough material (New York, Sydney, the Northern Territory, fall of the
Berlin Wall) to have succoured his 23rd and 24th ones as well. Here's to his
25th.
</TEXT>
