<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / FT Christmas Books: The pick of the publishing year - From
politics to poetry, history to humour - our writers choose the best books of
1994
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN McEWAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
I have read nothing so entertaining and intellectually stimulating this year
as Steven Pinker's The Language Instinct (Allen Lane, Pounds 20). He sets
out to demonstrate that language is not a cultural invention but a
neurological mechanism, and along the way offers up many witty and
fascinating reflections on anthropology, Darwinism, cultural snobbery, as
well as an elegant defence of 'hopefully' as a sentence adverb.
In Craig Raine's long poem History: The Home Movie (Penguin, Pounds 9.99)
language is wrought into a kind of mental jewellery; imagery of clarity and
fabulous invention shines on every page. The minutiae of the private life
and the great upheavals of this century are given equal weight to create a
history of intense emotional reality.
When modern warfare engulfs a literary mind the result is usually
interesting enough in itself, but Tobias Wolff's memoir of his time in
Vietnam, In Pharaoh's Army (Bloomsbury, Pounds 14.99), has an irresistible
flow. He is a lucid, self-honest spirit with a gift for narrative. I read
him at a sitting, and was sad to run out of pages.
</TEXT>
