<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / A-Z of Personal Finance (22): A new Aim for the small
company - Unlisted Securities Market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Unlisted Securities Market is scheduled to be put to rest at the end of
1996, and from the end of this year no new companies will be listed on it.
So what is an investor in smaller companies to do?
The USM was launched in 1981, largely in response to growing interest in
so-called over-the-counter stocks which were too small or too new to meet
the requirements of the London Stock Exchange's official list. And while it
enjoyed a surge of popularity in the mid- and late 1980s, trading trickled
to a virtual standstill as the recession began to eat its way through the
fortunes of smaller companies.
The decision to close the USM reflects the near-abandonment of the market by
both investors and listees, although, quite clearly, investors still want a
place where they can buy the shares of the smallest companies.
The current debate about what should replace the USM centres on two key
considerations. First, what is the desired level of investor protection
necessary to ensure a healthy market in small-company shares? And second,
what sort of exchange is most likely to stimulate investor interest in this
sector through good times and bad?
The London Stock Exchange thinks it has the answer. First, it has already
made several key changes to its official list, to make it easier for
biotechnology and healthcare companies to join. And second, it has proposed
an Alternative Investment Market (AIM), to list the shares of companies that
are either too small or whose shares are not traded widely enough to qualify
for the official list.
Whether the AIM will satisfy those who want to buy small-company shares
remains to be seen. For one thing, it is not clear that the tax advantages
available to those who have bought USM-listed shares - their inheritance tax
liability is reduced by 50 per cent - will be available.
Also, it would be up to investors to assess their own comfort with looser
regulation. The Stock Exchange has proposed that looser listing requirements
shall apply to this category of company; and no minimum threshold is
envisaged for length-of-trading record, market capitalisation or the
percentage of shares in public hands.
Moreover, it proposes that companies seeking a listing on the AIM shall not
be required to have a sponsor, charged with ensuring that due diligence has
been taken in preparing documentation for listing.
Mr David Jones, chairman of Sharelink, a share-dealing service for private
clients, argues that, as long as investors are fully aware of the risks they
are taking, they do not need excessive protection. 'What private investors
like is clarity,' he says. 'The proposition that you need lots of regulation
to encourage them is untested.'
However, others argue that investor protection is crucial to encourage
private investors to buy small-company shares, and that, moreover, such
shares need an exchange specifically devoted to promoting interest in the
sector. To this end, a group of European venture capitalists, the Paris
Bourse and the US-based Nasdaq stock market have announced plans for a new
pan-European market for small-company shares.
The market, intended to begin operation by late 1995, will allow investors
to buy shares in small companies across Europe. Regulation will be much
closer to that prevailing on Nasdaq; and companies will be required to have
an investment-banking sponsor and to report market-sensitive information
regularly.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
