<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / A-Z of Personal Finance (19): Quicker deals will help to
reduce risk
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINE BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Brokers used to do it at the end of every two or three weeks. Since the
summer, they have needed to do it after spells of 10 days. In a few months
they will be required to do it every five days.
They now are governed by rolling settlement on the stock market. It began in
July, and means that shares have to he delivered and paid for 10 days after
the original deal is struck.
This is the first phase of London's part in an international drive for the
reduction of settlement times, and therefore risk, in equity markets. Its
next move, in June, will be to a five-day settlement period. This will prove
far more of a leap than the 10-day move from the old account system, and is
already viewed with some caution in the market.
Ten-day settlement replaces two- and three-week trading accounts with
settlement taking place seven days after the end of those accounts. On a
typical two-week account, if a deal was struck on the first day of the
account, there would be three weeks before settlement had to be made.
Conversely, if a deal was struck on the last day of the account, then there
would be just a week until settlement. The Stock Exchange says that the
10-day stage was chosen as a mean average of the possibilities under the
previous accounts.
Rolling settlement means that every day is a settlement day for someone in
the market, unlike the old system of 24 days on which everyone made their
settlements.
Some investors have found that the generally speedier execution - and
penalties incurred from late action - has increased the attractions of
conducting investments via nominee accounts held at stockbrokers. In such
accounts, shares are registered in the name of the broker's nominee company
rather than the investor, thus enabling faster transactions.
Under 10-day settlement, it is not too difficult for a client to post share
certificates to his broker for delivery. It will not be as easy to do this
under five-day settlement. A five-day time-frame, however, runs hard up
against three-day cheque-clearance periods and possible postal delays.
Rolling settlement may now be well on course to roll faster, but it is not
unavoidable. As with anything in the market, investors can call their own
tunes if they are prepared to pay. At present, settlement may be made later
than 10 days, but the marketmakers do widen their price spreads to reflect
increased risk, and later settlement is a more costly exercise.
Risk reduction was one of the prime reasons for the introduction of rolling
settlement, with the possibility of failed trades lessened by a shorter
transaction time. The other main impetus was the internationalisation of
securities dealing.
The UK agreed in 1989 to introducerolling settlement, and so put in place a
similar framework to that in other leading financial centres. It was
responding to a call for swifter settlement in equity trading by the G30,
the Washington-based study group. Although the mechanics of settlement vary
between countries, the US operates rolling settlement on a five-day basis;
Japan on three days; France on three days; and Germany on two days.
The UK is aiming eventually for three-day settlement, but that is dependent
on the operation of paperless share-trading, which is some way off.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
