<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / A-Z of Personal Finance (18): How to spot a troubled company
 -Quick ratio
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The 'quick ratio', or 'acid-test ratio', is commonly seen as cutting to the
very heart of a business's viability, for it simply measures its ability to
pay its creditors in the short term.
Calculation of the ratio is straight-forward and requires the current assets
(minus the stock) to be divided by the current liabilities.
Ratios of less than 1.0 do not necessarily spell misery. A supermarket, for
example, because it sells goods for cash before paying for them, will often
operate with quick ratios well below one. In this sector 0.2 is common.
Therefore quick ratios should always be seen in relation to others in the
same sector and of the same type.
A declining trend in a quick ratio may signal trouble ahead. Underlying such
a trend might be a rising overdraft; and some sort of statement should
therefore be sought out in the annual accounts.
It is worth noting that, for this test, creditors falling due within one
year should be considered to be current liabilities, although under the
requirements of the Companies Act this is not always easy to work out.
A drawback to the quick ratio is that it was designed to examine the cash
flow of a company at a time when that was often obscured and the information
was not in the balance sheet or the profit-and-loss account.
Since the publication of Financial Reporting Standard 1, in 1992, companies
have been required to include a cash-flow statement, which replaces the much
discredited funds flow statement. Now, the information which the quick ratio
sought to illuminate is readily available.
The real problem with the quick ratio is that implied by its name.
Single-ratio appraisals of a company's worth are now frowned upon by the
regulators and standard setters unless they are used properly - and never in
isolation.
Allister Wilson, partner with Ernst and Young, accountants, and one of the
authors of the monumental UK GAAP (Generally Accepted Accounting
Principals), says the quick ratio is potentially dangerous and should be
used with care.
Anyone tempted should ask themselves: where is the cash, and where are the
creditors? Cross-border problems could undermine liquidity. And the problem
with current assets is that, although stock is taken out, other long-term
debits can creep in, such as that from a pension fund.
Mr Wilson prefers, in this particular case, to use the cash flow over the
total debt as a measure of liquidity - with the total debt including
off-balance sheet items like lease liabilities. But the warning is clear:
'One ratio means absolutely nothing.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
