<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Alternative Investment): Funeral wishes
ignored - Briefcase
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
We are a small firm of funeral directors. Some time ago, we were instructed
by a man who made quite clear that he wanted no service at either church or
crematorium, and his ashes to be buried with his brother. He died soon
after.
The closest relatives were two nephews, who were also executors. They
changed his wishes and had a church service, although we disagreed. Do
executors have a legal right to do this?
I believe this is more a moral than a legal problem although, clearly, the
executors should not alter the wishes of the deceased. I suggest you get
advice from a local solicitor. If the legal view is in accordance with the
above, then you could decline to act in future if you found an executor
wished to act against the wishes of the deceased. (Reply by Barry Stillerman
of accountant Stoy Hayward).
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All inquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
