<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Alternative Investment): No fantasy for the
man from Dallas - William Hall meets a small investor who has beaten the
professionals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM HALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mention Jayesh Manek and most City fund managers look blank. But this could
be about to change as Manek, a 38-year-old pharmacist from Ruislip,
Middlesex, has done what many small investors dream about and proved it is
possible to beat the professionals at their own game.
The Sunday Times is expected to announce this weekend that Manek has won the
Pounds 100,000 first prize in its Fantasy Fund Manager competition. Every
week since May, he has been pitting his wits against 40,000 other
contestants - including a fair sprinkling of investment professionals - to
see how much he could make from a hypothetical Pounds 10m invested in a
range of 250 genuine shares.
Despite operating during a period when the stock market has fallen, Manek's
wheeling and dealing means that his Pounds 10m JP Income fund is now worth
more than Pounds 500m. Altogether, he entered 28 separate funds, and eight
of the top 12 in the competition belong to him.
Admittedly, he has taken very big bets on very small shares and, in some
cases, has invested several times more than the market capitalisation of the
stock in question. In real life, that would have been impossible - and, when
it was possible, the share price would have run away long before he could
have invested a fraction of his money. But Manek's consistency in winning,
and his ability to spot small stocks that are just about to move, is due to
more than luck.
He emigrated to Britain from Uganda in 1971 and owes his early success to
his late uncle, BJ Manek, who is reckoned to have been the Financial Times'
first reader in Nairobi, Kenya, and also encouraged his nephew to read the
newspaper when not studying for his pharmacy exams in Sussex.
Soon, Manek had caught the stock market bug. He added the Investors
Chronicle to his reading list and started to play the traded options market.
Although Manek took delivery recently of a Reuter terminal, and has moved on
from reading Jim Slater's The Zulu Principle ('very good') to John Train's
The Money Masters and The New Money Masters ('very useful'), he remains
convinced that diligent reading of the IC and FT is enough to give the
private investor an edge when investing in stocks with a market
capitalisation of under Pounds 100m.
Most of the information on his biggest coups - such as Orb Estates,
Middlesex Holdings, United Breweries, Virtuality, Bullers, Anglo United and
CRP Leisure - has been gleaned from these sources. 'You are learning all the
time,' he says.
Manek, who monitors both the fundamentals and the charts, does not believe a
company warrants investment just because 'old so and so' has gone on the
board, but he always wants to see how a share price reacts to a boardroom
change. Share price movements can often send out the wrong signal but, for
Manek, they are the best indicator he has got.
Now that he has a Reuter screen, it is easier to monitor changes in
directors' shareholdings and volume figures. But that is not enough. 'The
biggest challenge is to know when to take a profit,' says Manek - and,
judging by his record in the Fantasy competition, this is where his real
skill lies, rather than in individual stock-picking.
He has a warning, though. With vivid memories of what happened when he once
fell in love with Glaxo options, he stresses: 'Never get emotionally
involved with a particular stock.'
Manek is the first to admit that he could do nowhere near as well if he was
investing his own money rather than the fantasy funds of the Sunday Times.
As for whether any City fund manager would want to hire him, he says he has
yet to be approached.
Foreign &amp; Colonial's Michael Hart, who admits he has never heard of Manek,
refuses to believe anyone can turn in such a consistent performance year
after year. Legal &amp; General's David Manning says that if Manek did have a
future in the City, it would be in a highly-geared hedge fund prepared to
take big bets.
Not that it matters, as Manek is not looking for a highly-paid spot in the
City. His job is helping his brother run the family's chain of Dallas
chemist shops, which he finds just as challenging intellectually as the
stock market. They started the business in 1980 and now have eight stores,
including a rather glitzy affair in London's Charing Cross station.
Indeed, when it comes to this specialist sector, Manek probably knows just
as much, if not more, than the big guns at Boots, Lloyds Chemists, Unichem
and AAH Holdings. As a businessman who likes playing the market in the UK
and India, it would be surprising if the Fantasy Fund Manager competition is
the last we hear of the man from Dallas.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
