<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / A-Z of Personal Finance (15): Treat them the same as other
shares - New issues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This year has seen investors deluged with prospectuses from companies
floating on the stock market. Not since the mid-1980s has the new-issue
market been so active.
Yet there is an important difference this time. Ten years ago, new issues
were an easy way to make money. Many were hugely underpriced, leading to a
flood of applications and big premiums over the offer price when the shares
started trading. For the so-called 'stags', who applied for shares only to
sell them as soon as possible, there were good profits to be made.
By contrast, most investors in new issues in 1994 have suffered paper
losses. New issues are priced in relation to the general level of shares, so
if the market as a whole falls, as it has done since February, so will
shares in recent new issues. Overall, new issues have performed no worse
than the market as a whole.
Yet the expectation would have been for them to perform slightly better,
because new issues are priced to give a reasonable premium over the offer
price when they start trading in the market.
The problem has been a few disastrous flotations, where the shares have
fallen sharply not long afterwards. While these flops have scared many
private investors off, new issues do still have some attractions.
The first is simply convenience. The Stock Exchange requires that the
largest flotations must be conducted through a public offer for sale. Under
an offer, anyone can apply for shares, and the process involves no more than
filling in a form printed in the newspapers and sending it off with a
cheque.
(In smaller flotations, shares are sold via placings or intermediaries'
offers, and are only available to private investors if they happen to be
clients of the particular stockbrokers involved.)
Another advantage of buying shares when a company floats is that there is no
commission to pay. If the shares are priced at Pounds 1 each, Pounds 1 is
what you pay.
In theory, a more valuable saving is that the shares are priced so that they
go to a premium in the market. But in the volatile conditions seen during
most of 1994 this has not always happened.
One of the biggest claimed selling points for new issues is that it is the
least risky time in a company's life at which to invest. In preparation for
flotation, a company's business and finances will have been scrutinised by
its merchant bank, stockbroker and accountants. They put their names to the
prospectus, and will be severely embarrassed if anything goes wrong shortly
after flotation.
But recent experience shows that this is very far from a guarantee. There is
even an argument that flotation is a positively bad time at which to invest,
because the shares are unlikely to be seriously undervalued. Those looking
for bargains might be better advised to consider shares of neglected or
unfashionable companies already trading on the stock market.
The best policy for investors is to treat new issues no differently from
other shares, and to judge them on the same basis.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
