<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Investment and Saving): New issues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Wiltshire-based regional brewer this week became the latest victim of the
bruised new issues market, writes David Blackwell. Ushers, a product of the
government's anti-monopoly ruling, intended to raise around Pounds 50m to
clear debt through a placing and open offer, but the issue was pulled on
Thursday - the very day the issue price was due to be announced.
Institutions were willing to put up only three-quarters of the necessary
money and the group felt that, unless the shares were placed fully ahead of
the public offer, it would risk a bad after-market.
That seems wise following the surreal events at United Carriers which, on
Monday, issued its second profits warning since flotation in February. The
first cited a lack of parcels; the second, an excess. The shares fell 79p to
almost half the flotation price.
RAP Group, a rubber and plastics distributor, yesterday curbed its ambition
to raise Pounds 4.6m from a placing, settling instead for Pounds 3.55m. The
shares were priced at 142p, giving a market capitalisation of Pounds 15.08m.
Meanwhile, investors thinking of going for shares in BSkyB should be aware
of this week's report from Henderson Crosthwaite suggesting the flotation
greatly over-values the satellite television venture.
</TEXT>
