<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / How to Spend It: Strong scents of occasion - Lucia van der
Post carries a flame for a sweet-smelling home
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LUCIA VAN DER POST
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
I first became interested in sweet smells for the house when my son kept
hamsters, and even though the creatures were banished to the cellar (animal
rights activists can relax, these were the days when he was small and I knew
no better), an aroma began to waft around the house that was, shall we say.
. . musty.
Most of us have less urgent reasons for perfuming the house. We simply find
a sweet-smelling home as essential to our sense of well-being as comfortable
sofas and fresh coffee. And candles are a quick and cheap way of adding
magic to any room.
The success of Wax Lyrical, a small niche-chain of 21 shops selling nothing
but candles, is proof that once people have discovered the charm of candles,
they become addicted.
Marjorie Bannister and Mark Chessel started the business on a hunch. While
on a trip to Iceland, they were enchanted by the way candles were used in
Icelandic homes and became convinced that the British would take to using
them if only they were made more accessible. Their initial research revealed
that 95 per cent of British people only ever used candles at Christmas.
Since Bannister and Chessel opened their first specialist candle-only shop
in Richmond, the market in the UK has grown by leaps and bounds.
Some of the cheapest and most seductive scents are aromatherapy candles,
which are infused with essential oils. These come in little stone pots, and
cost Pounds 4.95, the most popular scents being sandalwood and ylang-ylang.
Minimalists who would never use anything but plain cream will find classic
ivory church candles in all sizes and prices. For more baroque tastes, there
is an opulent Russian range. Matt-gold, rose-shaped candles floating over a
bed of glass nuggets, gold orbs, or taper candles with rich fluted glass
candle-holders and crystal grapes would cater perfectly for romantics.
Anybody who remembers dear old Price's candles will be amazed at what the
company is up to now - wax-filled tin buckets and mugs, diamond tea-lights,
hanging lanterns, as well as a wide range of candles scented with citronella
essence, which will not only suffuse the house with a tangy, lemony scent
but will also keep midges away. And for the purists, the firm still sells
its classic range.
Annick Goutal (stocked by Harrods, Selfridges, Harvey Nichols, The Conran
Shop and Liberty as well as selected out-of-London shops) offers natural
stones impregnated with essences. These sit on a diffuser placed over a
light bulb and give off a subtle but delicious scent. They cost Pounds 39.50
and the scents are Fleur Blanche, Eau d'Hadrien, Rose Absolue, Passion and
Sables.
A specialist shop for all things fragrant is L'Artisan Parfumeur, 17 Cale
Street, London SW3 (071-352 4196).
The fragrance Ambre comes as a burning oil costing Pounds 21.95 for an
applicator top and two pressed ceramic rings. It also comes as a room spray
at Pounds 18.95, and for musty cars there is L'Eau de l'Auto Ambre at Pounds
16.50. However, most luxurious of all are the terracotta pomanders, filled
with ambergris, which provide a wonderful perfume in a wardrobe or chest of
drawers.
Tisserand is another name to look out for. It specialises in essential oils
and has a vast range of candles scented with everything from jasmine to
orange-blossom or sandalwood.
For occasions when use of a flame would be dangerous, it stocks two electric
devices. The first, the Aromastone (Pounds 23.90), comes in a little round
pot that gives off the scent of sandalwood, frankincense and other
fragrances from a range. The second, the Aromastream, which comes in a
little white unit (Pounds 23.90), looks boring but it dispenses cooler
fragrances, such as citrus.
My own personal preferences run to house-scents that veer towards the subtle
and understated and it is hard to beat the classics such as Rigaud's Cypres,
which costs Pounds 49.95 at The Conran Shop, and Czech &amp; Speake's plain
frosted-glass containers filled with candles perfumed with frankincense and
myrrh, rose and mimosa and costing Pounds 25 each.
Anybody who has ever been to Florence may have paid a visit to the Farmacia
Santa Maria Novella, which claims to be the oldest pharmacy in the world. A
branch has now opened at 117 Walton Street, selling the same delectably
perfumed lotions and potions. In particular, look out for Armeneia paper,
which is burnt to scent the air, perfumed drawer-lining paper and a
refreshing mint soap that repels insects.
Another little shop, La Bougie, has been open only two months at 5
Montpelier Street, Knightsbridge, London SW7 and specialises in nothing but
candles and candle appurtenances. It is modelled on the Paris shop of the
same name and is the place to look for strong and dramatic candelabra
(Pounds 80), wrought-iron candle-stands for floating candles (Pounds 11.80),
or a wrought-iron stand over 2ft high with a glass bowl for floating candles
(Pounds 95). And if by now you are tired of candles, you can restore your
flagging spirits with a glass of champagne and some seafood in the champagne
and oyster bar in the basement.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P5999 Miscellaneous Retail Stores, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
