<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / A-Z of Personal Finance (11): Back smaller companies and be
patient - Japanese markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Japan seemed the place to be for many investors early this year. After falls
in other stock markets around the world this spring, Tokyo was the only
place where optimism seemed justified.
The market there was still at less than half its peak level. Deregulation
and restructuring of the Japanese economy and industry seemed to promise new
opportunities for growth, and economic recovery looked set to take off. For
a while, it seemed that the stock market would follow suit - but its
performance has been disappointing.
While foreign fund managers poured money into the market in the first half
of the year, Japanese individuals and institutions kept their hands in their
pockets and their money on deposit. The main Nikkei index is no higher than
it was for most of 1993, and in late November it slipped below 19,000 for
the first time in nine months.
The over-the-counter market (OTC) in smaller companies fell just as
dramatically as the main index in 1990, only to rise again, then fall yet
further by mid-1992. It has since bounced back a little, with the first
signs of a recovery. Overall, the OTC market has outperformed the main
Nikkei index substantially over the last five years.
Some investors have taken advantage of this trend by putting their money
into unit and investment trusts specialising in Japanese smaller companies.
It is no surprise that three of the five top-performing Japanese unit trusts
over a five-year period are specialists in smaller companies - two trusts
managed by Schroders and one by Dunedin. Of course, outperformance by
smaller companies tends to be cyclical.
In the late 1980s, Tokyo was briefly the world's biggest stock market. It is
now back in second place, behind New York, but still deserves a place in
every serious investor's portfolio. The main choice for private investors is
between general Japan funds (there is a broad choice of both unit and
investment trusts) and those concentrating on smaller companies. Or, if you
prefer to spread your bets a little, you could pick a fund that invests in
the whole of the Far East including Japan.
More obsure areas, such as warrants or corporate bonds, can be exciting, but
are rarely accessible to individuals with modest amounts of money to invest.
Buying individual Japanese stocks is not recommended for private
individuals.
The Japanese stock market often moves in a different direction from the rest
of the world, so it can be seen as a useful way of lowering risk and
diversifying your portfolio. However, currency fluctuations can complicate
matters: the strong yen has worked in favour of British investors recently,
but the situation could well be reversed in future.
Although Tokyo has been a disappointment so far this year, many analysts say
that the good times have only been postponed, not cancelled. The recovery
has been a little slower than expected, but Tokyo may still be a good home
for a little of your savings if you can afford to wait a few years for your
rewards.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
