<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / A-Z of Personal Finance (7): Why what you see is not what
you get - Forward pricing
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
   Martin MacConnol
Nobody enjoys buying goods 'sight unseen' - which explains why some aspiring
investors are deterred by the forward-pricing system most unit trust funds
now adopt.
Forward pricing means that what you see is not what you get. If you are
buying or selling units today, you will not receive the price listed in the
current FT for forward-priced units (denoted by an 'F' in the listings).
Instead, the price you will receive is determined by the next valuation of
the fund after you place your order (most unit trusts value their units once
a day).
All this has the immediate look of a system which probably helps the fund
manager but not the investor. For instance, if you spot a rising market and
wish to buy into it, your money will get you less than you might have hoped
for - since you will only receive units at the rate of the next valuation.
Similarly, if your units are going through the floor, they will have sunk
even further by the time you sell - because, again, their worth is
determined at the next valuation.
So why do most unit trusts use forward pricing, rather than the alternative
'What you see is what you get' historic system (denoted by an 'H' in the FT
listings)?
Forward pricing gives existing investors more security. On any one day, only
a small minority of people are likely to be either buying or selling units
in a particular unit trust. Most will still have their money in the pot, and
it is their interests the fund manager is thinking about first and foremost.
With historic pricing, the assumption is that, on any given day, the fund
manager should be able to buy or sell units at the price listed in that
day's paper - ie, at yesterday's price. But prices move, and if the fund
manager is committed to historic pricing it could cost the overall fund to
pay yesterday's value for units.
Fund managers are confident that forward pricing is the more realistic way
of valuing units. You can even insist on having units forward priced by
those funds which still use the historic system.
For some people, forward pricing simply contributes to the confusion that
surrounds unit trusts; and much is being done to make them more
comprehensible to the ordinary investor.
Newspapers are no longer required to publish the cancellation price (the
lowest price at which the fund will buy back your units). Also, the prices
at which you can buy and sell units are now listed clearly as 'buying' and
'selling' prices in the FT, instead of under the old-fashioned and oblique
'bid/offer' titles. Next year, even this refinement is likely to be
superseded. It is expected that unit trusts will be given a single price
that refers to both buying and selling, in a further attempt to make them
easier to understand.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6211 Security Brokers and Dealers.
    P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
