<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Budget Analysis): Interest aid is axed -
Mortgages
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MEASURE: Borrowers taking out new mortgages after October 1 1995 will
not be able to claim income support to cover interest payments for the first
nine months of unemployment, redundancy and incapacity.
Existing borrowers will receive nothing for the first two months and only 50
per cent of mortgage interest for the next four months. From April 1995,
income support will not cover amounts borrowed above Pounds 100,000.
WHAT IT MEANS: The two largest high street mortgage lenders, the Halifax and
Abbey National, both confirmed they did not intend to make mortgage payment
insurance a condition of lending. But if smaller lenders move in this
direction, the cost of mortgages for new borrowers after October 1995 could
rise by more than Pounds 20 a month for a typical Pounds 50,000 endowment
mortgage.
Jill Mayman, spokesman for the Council of Mortgage Lenders says: 'Borrowers
considered a high risk because they are self-employed, on a low income or
disabled may be refused cover and could be forced out of the owner-occupier
sector.'
At present, income support covers 50 per cent of mortgage interest payments
for the first 16 weeks of a claim and 100 per cent thereafter, subject to a
cap on the mortgage of Pounds 125,000.
The number of claims has risen greatly in recent years, from 300,000 in 1988
at a cost of Pounds 286m to 548,000 in 1994 costing Pounds 1.082bn. The
government's plans will shift part of this burden to the private insurance
market.
Derek Roberts, chief executive of the Yorkshire Building Society, which has
150,000 borrowers, says: 'We will consider whether this insurance should be
compulsory. One-third of our new borrowers already have cover.'
According to the Halifax, the biggest lender with 1.8m mortgage accounts,
only 10 per cent of its borrowers have mortgage payment insurance at present
and spokesman Mark Hemingway says: 'We have no plans at present to make this
type of insurance compulsory. But we are concerned that borrowers who are
not covered could see their homes repossessed if they become unemployed and
cannot afford the interest payments.' Under the Halifax scheme, the monthly
cost is Pounds 6.90 for every Pounds 100 of cover while Abbey National's
version costs Pounds 6.95 for every Pounds 100. For a Pounds 50,000
endowment mortgage with monthly repayments of Pounds 297, this would cost
Pounds 21 a month.
Ian Darby, marketing director with independent mortgage adviser John
Charcol, adds: 'To date, most people who have asked for this insurance have
had some concern about their job security. As a result, claims have been
high, which has led to complex underwriting procedures with lots of
exclusions.' Darby urges lenders to take out block re-insurance to cover
mortgage liabilities. 'Alternatively, borrowers could pay a single premium
to cover the first year of unemployment, after which time they could claim
income support.'
</TEXT>
