FT  03 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Budget Analysis): Small savers are hit - SAYE
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE MEASURE: Save as you earn (SAYE) 'ordinary' schemes
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
available at building societies - have been abolished. National Savings is
to withdraw its Yearly Plan from February 1 1995.
WHAT IT MEANS: These two measures have squeezed out small, regular savers.
The popular, government-operated SAYE scheme was available at building
societies and the Abbey National bank. It was a monthly savings plan with a
minimum of Pounds 1 and a maximum of Pounds 20. At the end of five years,
the investor would receive tax-free interest equivalent to an annual 8.3 per
cent.
'We are very disappointed,' says Abbey National, which has 250,000 SAYE
accounts. 'It was one of the few accounts allowing the man in the street to
take advantage of tax-free opportunities.'
According to the government, SAYE was abolished to simplify tax-incentive
savings schemes and because it had been superseded by tax-exempt special
savings accounts. Unlike Tessas, however, the terms and conditions of SAYE
were the same from every provider.
Existing SAYE schemes are not affected.
National Savings will be dropping its Yearly Plan in 1995. This was designed
to help those who want to buy a National Savings certificate, Monthly
payments of between Pounds 20 and Pounds 400 are made by standing order for
12 months to buy a four-year Yearly Plan certificate.
The tax-free return after five years is 5.85 per cent a year compound.
Customers with existing Yearly Plan agreements can complete their payments
to get their next certificate.
