<PROFILE>_AN-ELDARADYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941203
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / Easing the pain of a prostate: A dramatic new technique
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Having your prostate 'cooked' by microwaves might not seem the most pleasant
way to spend a Tuesday afternoon but it does appear to offer a
revolutionary, cost-saving way to treat one of the most common medical
disorders afflicting middle-aged and older men.
One in three over 50 has difficulty urinating, mainly because the prostate
gland - which sits below the bladder, with the urethra passing through it -
enlarges with age. This constricts the urethra, slowing urine flow and
making it impossible to empty the bladder completely.
In only a small proportion of cases - about one in 27 - is cancer involved.
For most, the swelling is benign. But it becomes dangerous over time if
retained urine becomes infected, or affects the working of the bladder, or
backs up into kidneys where it can cause stones or permanent damage.
The conventional treatment is a prostate operation - rather similar to
coring an apple - to make the hole through the middle of the gland larger.
It entails between four and 10 days in hospital, carries risks from general
anaesthesia and bleeding - the prostate has an abundant blood supply - a
long recovery, and an outside chance of post-operative impotence.
The new treatment uses microwaves to heat up the gland to around 70`C and
'cook' it. The microwaves are emitted by a specially-designed
radio-frequency antenna inserted along the urethra.
To keep its effect localised within the prostate, iced water circulates
through the catheter carrying the antenna. A balloon thermometer in the
rectum - right next to the prostate - monitors temperature and switches off
the machine if things get too hot.
No general anaesthetic is needed - just a 'local' for the urethra, plus an
injection of pain-killers and sedatives into a vein if discomfort becomes
too great during the 90-minute procedure.
What happens is that a third-degree burn is inflicted, killing cells and
nerves. The dead cells are absorbed naturally by the body over the next 10
weeks or so. The results are proving similar or better than having a
conventional operation.
It sounds unpleasant and - as someone who had the procedure performed one
Tuesday afternoon in August - I can assure you it is. But you go home within
hours of treatment, usually the same day.
A catheter remains inserted until the initial swelling caused by the
treatment dies down, but it is removed at the hospital a few days later.
After that, nature takes its course. In many cases, patients have been back
at work within two weeks and well on the way to full recovery after six.
The treatment was invented by Urologix Inc, a Minneapolis company backed by
Dollars 15m of US venture capital. Chief executive Jack Meyer says the
average conventional prostate operation in the US costs between Dollars
8,000 and Dollars 10,000. The microwave technique will cut these costs by at
least half and release hospital beds for other cases.
Complications have been infrequent, although I developed an infection and
prostatic ulcers which took six weeks to heal. But, as a result, Urologix
says it can re-design its special catheter and cooling system to minimise
the risk to other patients in the future.
So far, more than 150 men have been treated at five centres. Two are in the
UK - the Royal Liverpool University Hospital and the East Surrey Hospital at
Redhill - while the others are the Mayo Clinic in Scottsdale, Arizona; the
Abbott Northwestern Hospital in Minneapolis; and the University of Manitoba
Hospital in Winnipeg, Canada.
The US Food and Drugs Administration has now approved the treatment for use
at six other hospitals there and it will be introduced into a German and a
French hospital in the new year.
The attraction to British politicians and health service administrators is
the potential saving. Keith Parsons, a Royal Liverpool consultant urologist
who is in charge of the new technique, does 300 conventional prostate
operations a year with his team. There is a 12-month waiting list, not least
because they consume more than 1,200 bed-days a year.
Theoretically, 10 patients a week could be microwaved with no need for a
hospital stay, but three single-day visits are required to ensure patients
are suitable for treatment and make preparations.
Theoretically, too, the treatment could be given in a health centre, or at a
group practice of general practitioners, or in a urologist's consulting
rooms. But Parsons always prefers to do it in hospital where support is at
hand immediately if anything goes wrong.
Parsons' own role is crucial to proving the new technique because, of all
the hospitals involved, the Royal Liverpool is collecting the most detailed
scientific data on every patient. This will be presented to conferences of
US and British urologists in about six months.
The benefits, however, go well beyond what might be expected from solving
what is basically a plumbing problem. For, once the kidneys are again being
flushed properly, general health blooms and the risk of kidney stones -
which have put me in hospital as an emergency case twice in the past three
years - diminish.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P806  Hospitals.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Services &amp; Services use.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT944-5417</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-ELDARADXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941203
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Budget Analysis): New unit trusts will
qualify for Peps
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Oeics - open-ended investment companies - the new type of unit trusts
scheduled to materialise in the UK next summer, will be able to qualify for
Peps on the same terms as authorised unit trusts, writes Scheherazade
Daneshkhu.
Regulations will also be brought in to allow some European institutions to
market Peps in the UK. Under the EU's Investment Services Directive, due to
come into force in 1996, brokers in an EU country will have access to the
markets of other member countries.
Oeics will issue shares instead of units and will have a single pricing
structure instead of the unit trust dual system of bid and offer prices
(buying and selling prices). Their formation will enable UK-based fund
management companies to market their funds in Europe. Rules will also be
made allowing existing unit trusts to convert into an Oeic.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
