<PROFILE>_AN-ELDARADVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941203
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Budget Analysis): A modest advance for
private investors - Gilts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MEASURE: The Bank of England is planning to introduce an open
re-purchase (or 'repo') market for UK government securities or gilts. One
potential consequence is that interest on all gilts may start to be paid
gross of tax.
WHAT IT MEANS: The development of a gilt repo market would bring the UK into
line with most other international bond markets. Repos are loans between two
parties in which bonds are used as collateral. Party A lends its gilts to
Party B in return for cash up-front. At the end of a set period, Party A
re-purchases the gilts at a set price which reflects an interest payment
covering the period of the loan.
The Bank of England believes that creating a repo facility will add
liquidity to the gilts market by encouraging more investors to take part. In
the long run, this should reduce the government's borrowing costs. But the
introduction of such a system, while very useful to institutional investors
wishing to finance their gilt holdings, or to traders who want to speculate
on a fall in gilt prices by 'going short', will have little direct impact on
the private investor. Repos are definitely designed for professionals.
It is the side-effects of a repo system which may matter to the average
investor. A repo system would be made more complex by the fact that some
investors receive their interest gross while others get it only after
witholding tax is deducted.
One change that would make the system run more smoothly is for interest on
all gilts to be paid gross of tax. 'It is possible to have a gilt repo
market without gross payment of interest but I don't think it would be
satisfactory to the market' says Roger Shaw, head of arbitrage at Mildland
Global Markets.
Investors would then be responsible for declaring the tax payable to the
Inland Revenue.
Unsurprisingly, the Revenue fears it could lose money through the change.
The present witholding tax system is a highly effective way of collecting
money due.
The Revenue is soon going to produce a consultation paper on the subject.
Like the Bank of England's paper, issued this week, it will invite comments
by January 31. The Bank says the earliest likely date for a fully
functioning repo market would then be July 31.
Gross interest on gilts would make them more convenient for wealthier
non-taxpayers, such as non-working spouses. At present, they can receive
tax-free income on gilts via the National Savings Stock Register. If,
however, you hold gilts already, the amount of any one gilt you can transfer
to the NSSR is Pounds 5,000 a year. Then, too, new buyers of gilts can buy
only Pounds 25,000 of any one stock in one day. And, because the NSSR is a
postal system, it is slower than operating via a broker; it also means
investors are unsure of the price they will get.
Buying via the NSSR is cheaper than buying through a broker but not as cheap
as it used to be; charges were increased this week from an effective 0.4 per
cent to 0.6.
So, while gross payment of interest would be a modest step forward for the
private investor, it would not be a revolution - especially as the
possibility of tax-free income from corporate bonds and preference shares is
now on offer from the chancellor.
Gilt reaction, Page 6
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
