<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / A-Z of Personal Finance (3): Extra cost, but extra service
too - Broker unit trusts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANET WALFORD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A broker unit trust forms a separate part of a unit trust of a host company
 -such as a unit trust group or life insurance company, which retains legal
ownership - but with investment advice provided either by a stockbroker or
independent financial adviser.
The broker or adviser has to obtain special permission from the Personal
Investment Authority (PIA), the Investment Managers Regulatory Organisation
(Imro) or the Securities and Futures Association (SFA) before he can offer
broker unit trusts.
The biggest host company of broker unit trusts is Old Mutual (which this
month changed its name from Providence Capitol), with about Pounds 70m under
its control. The host company has the power to withdraw the adviser's
investment management role if it feels the adviser is no longer fit and
proper to run the fund's investments; in which case the host company may
absorb the broker fund monies into its own unit trust or manage them itself.
Because the broker unit trust forms part of the unit trust company, the
investments have to be within unit trust legislation and regulation. This
will include shares quoted on any recognised worldwide stock exchange,
futures, derivatives and so on.
With the host company and broker both involved in running the broker unit
trust, all charges are split between the two. The initial charge will be
shared out to cover the broker's or adviser's commission and the management
company's administration. The annual management charge is also shared.
However, the charges on broker unit trusts are usually higher than those
levied by the underlying unit trust.
There are basically two types of broker unit trust: the securities version,
and the fund-of-funds version. The securities version invests directly in
shares and securities to achieve a specific investment objective. By
contrast, the fund-of-funds trust involves clients of a similar investment
profile, being invested in one unit trust which then invests in a range of
others to provide the required spread of investments with attendant saving
on costs boosting efficiency.
One big advantage of investing in fund-of-funds broker unit trusts is that
capital gains tax can be kept to a minimum. Through bed-and-breakfasting,
the liability can be diminished even further to almost nil. A broker unit
trust manager can make one transaction within his fund on behalf of many
clients without CGT, buying in bulk at competitive prices.
A broker unit trust is basically an asset allocation and administration
tool, which provides an extra level of service paid for by a higher
management charge. As such, the broker unit trust can offer a worthwhile
financial planning vehicle, and the fund-of-funds version offers a
cost-effective way of replacing the discretionary unit trust portfolio
management service, with the added benefit of closer dialogue with the
investment manager (the broker).
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6726 Investment Offices, NEC.
    P6211 Security Brokers and Dealers.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
