<PROFILE>_AN-ELDARADSFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941203
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / A-Z of Personal Finance (2): Top up your income for
retirement - Additional voluntary contributions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nine out of 10 employees retire on a lower pension than the maximum
permitted by the Inland Revenue, yet few take advantage of a readily
available, tax-efficient method of topping up their retirement income.
The simplest and cheapest way to top up is through your employer's
additional voluntary contribution (AVC) scheme, which runs in conjunction
with the main pension scheme. Almost without exception, all company pension
schemes must offer an AVC facility, although in most cases the investment
and administration is sub-contracted to a third party - usually a life
office, unit trust group or building society.
A second option is an individual arrangement known as a 'free-standing' AVC.
FSAVCs are sold by the same providers as the in-house variety, but in this
case your employer is not involved.
The Inland Revenue allows you to pay up to 15 per cent of your pensionable
salary into your main company scheme and AVC scheme combined (restricted in
the case of some higher earners). Most employees pay about 6 per cent to
their main scheme, so this leaves plenty of scope for additional
contributions.
Under Revenue rules the only time you can pay in to an AVC or FSAVC is when
you are a member of a company pension scheme. Both arrangements qualify for
full tax relief on employee contributions (employers cannot contribute) and
tax-free growth of the fund. AVCs may also provide a tax-free cash lump-sum
at retirement if contributions were started before April 1987. There is no
tax-free cash option with FSAVCs.
Performance is critical with additional contributions. Your main company
scheme is likely to provide a pension linked to salary, but in most cases
your top-up fund will be used to buy an annuity from a life office to
provide regular (taxed) income in retirement. The level of income you secure
is largely dictated by the size of your fund.
It is also important to check for flexibility - you should be able to pay
what you like, when you like, without penalty (within Revenue limits, of
course).
In theory, your employer's AVC scheme should provide better value than an
FSAVC, because employers usually bear some or all of the provider's costs.
With an FSAVC you pay all these charges yourself.
However, AVC investment choices can be limited - for example, you may only
be offered a building society deposit account. If you have more than five
years to go to retirement you might want a with-profits, unit-linked or
unit-trust fund, which provide various degrees of exposure to stock market
growth.
Do check the level of charges and the performance, though. With more than
100 FSAVCs on the market - each offering a range of funds - it is essential
to seek independent advice.
Finally, bear in mind that AVCs and FSAVCs usually lock away your money
until you retire from your main company scheme. If you want more
flexibility, consider a personal equity plan, available from stockbrokers
and independent advisers, or, for the very cautious, a tax exempt special
savings account (Tessa), from building societies and banks.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6371 Pension, Health, and Welfare Funds.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
