<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Budget Analysis): Relief for adventurers -
High risk investments / The new tax advantages for investors in small,
unquoted companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MEASURE: Better tax breaks for investing in small unquoted companies via
the enterprise investment scheme (EIS) and venture capital trusts (VCTs).
The chancellor added capital gains tax re-investment relief to the 20 per
cent up-front income tax relief available already on investments of up to
Pounds 100,000 through the EIS. Investors in VCTs - which come into
existence on April 6 - will be entitled to the same combination of 20 per
cent up-front relief on investments up to Pounds 100,000, plus CGT
re-investment relief, as well as tax-free income and capital gains from the
trust.
In both cases, the initial income tax relief applies only if the investments
are held for at least five years.
WHAT IT MEANS: Re-investment relief (or 'rollover relief') from CGT is an
idea the chancellor introduced in the 1993 Budget. It allows investors to
defer a CGT liability on gains made from any investment - shares, art works,
a second home - if the gains are re-invested in an unquoted trading company.
Initially, the relief was limited to direct investments in companies not
using the EIS, but this has now been broadened to include both the EIS and
VCTs.
As CGT is charged at 40 per cent, this means that when re-investment relief
is combined with the 20 per cent up-front tax relief on EIS companies or
VCTs, investors may be entitled to a total of 60 per cent tax relief. And as
each person is entitled to relief on investments of up to Pounds 100,000 a
year in both EIS companies and VCTs, this adds up to 60 per cent tax relief
on investments of Pounds 200,000 a year.
The tax charge on gains rolled over into EIS companies, VCTs or other
unquoted companies does not disappear, however: it is merely postponed until
the investor disposes of the new investment. In any case, the shares must be
held for at least five years to qualify for the 20 per cent income tax
relief.
If you have subscribed already for shares in a company issued under the EIS,
you might still be able to take advantage of the new rollover relief. This
applies to investments disposed of on, or after, Budget day; but it is
available when the subscription for shares under the EIS is made up to one
year before, or three years after, the disposal.
This Budget also made it easier for companies to qualify under EIS rules by
relaxing restrictions on property-holding. Previously, a company lost EIS
status if, at any stage, land or buildings accounted for more than half its
assets. This was intended to rule out low risk schemes which proliferated
under the predecessor to the EIS, the business expansion scheme (BES) - such
as companies buying properties to let out under assured short-term tenancy
agreements.
Given, however, that business premises are often a company's biggest asset,
this rule ended up disqualifying many companies which fell within the scope
intended originally by the chancellor. Companies specialising in letting out
residential property will still be excluded from the EIS.
A few other minor changes were made to relax the EIS rules concerning
companies under common control, rights issues, and mergers.
In the first 11 months of its life, the EIS has not attracted investors at
the same rate as the BES. Most industry insiders have blamed this lack of
success on the tighter rules (which mean that only companies at the riskier
end of the old BES spectrum can qualify for the EIS), and on the lack of
generous sweeteners.
Likewise, when the outline proposals for VCTs were published, offering only
tax-free income and capital gains but no up-front relief, many people voiced
doubts about whether Pep-style tax breaks would be enough to entice
investors into the much riskier territory of venture capital.
The Budget changes go at least some way towards rectifying those situations.
But investors should not throw caution to the wind.
Albert Nawrocki, senior tax manager at accountant Binder Hamlyn, warns:
'Whilst the tax advantages obviously make both the venture capital trusts
and EIS much more attractive, investors should not lose sight of the
commercial viability of the underlying investment.'
EIS companies and VCTs are very high-risk investments. Both are ways of
generating money for small businesses in an early stage of their
development. Companies which have used the EIS so far have been involved in
activities ranging from film production, stubble-burning, pub management,
and even promoting a new type of musical instrument.
These are hardly mainstream investments, and there is no protection for
investors in the not-so-unlikely event of their collapse. The one
consolation is that with the EIS, unlike the BES, losses can be offset
against CGT or income tax. Yet, offsetting a loss is hardly the same as
making a profit.
VCTs will invest in similar small developing companies. Although VCTs spread
the risk a little by giving investors stakes in a range of companies, a few
of the investments are almost bound to fail - so investors must hope the
performance of the successes will more than make up for the failures.
An additional complication is that because VCTs will function like normal
investment trusts, it is likely their shares will trade at a discount to net
asset value - so, within a few weeks of launch, investors could see their
holding fall in value by 10 or 15 per cent.
This could wipe out much of the benefit of the initial income tax relief
(which is available only to investors subscribing for new shares in a trust,
not to anyone buying shares in the market). The value might not be recovered
for several years, if ever.
If any of these prospects worry you, you should stick to other tax-efficient
investments like Tessas and Peps. Always remember that no matter how
generous the tax incentives, you should never be tempted by them into making
an investment you would not have considered otherwise.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
