<HEADLINE>
FT  03 DEC 94 / The Lex Column: RJB Mining
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The 11 per cent cut in the price RJB Mining is paying for English Coal may
look like smart haggling. But it makes little difference to its financial
prospects. RJB is getting less for less: most of the Pounds 99m reduction
can be accounted for by lower stocks and greater liabilities. Admittedly,
the lower price allows RJB to cancel its Pounds 100m corporate bond. That,
together with the opportunity to defer part of the payment, may help reduce
interest payments and improve cash-flow, but only marginally.
Until April 1998, when the electricity generators' fixed contracts expire,
English Coal will enjoy strong cash flow. By the end of that period, RJB
should have paid off its bank debt. The problem for equity investors remains
forecasting what happens thereafter. Investors have limited objective advice
to call on. There is a dearth of City expertise and the specialist
consultants' forecasts diverge considerably. With so much still uncertain,
it is unfortunate the gap between the prospectus' publication and the
offer's close will be just one week.
The company's long-term attraction will be dependent on the accuracy of
RJB's ambitious assumptions for volumes and prices after 1998. Much depends
on RJB's ability to cut costs sufficiently so it can deliver coal cheaply
enough to keep out imports. RJB has proved highly successful at open-cast
mining, but its relative inexperience in deep mines is worrying. For equity
investors, RJB is a high-risk company. The price, when set, will need to
reflect that.
</TEXT>
